{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3ca9a72a-5e97-4c6d-8a21-c998c40af376","content":"Create a `.vscode/mcp.json` file in your workspace with a `stdio` transport that runs your server via `dotnet run`:\n\n```jsonc\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`command`/`args`** — launches your server with `dotnet run`. Paths are relative to the workspace root.\n- If your server uses environment variables, add an `\"env\"` object (e.g., `\"env\": { \"MY_VAR\": \"value\" }`).\n- Make sure your server reads from stdin and writes to stdout (the standard MCP stdio transport).\n\nAfter saving, open the Command Palette (`Ctrl+Shift+P`) → **MCP: List Servers** to verify it's detected. Copilot agent mode will then discover and use the tools your server exposes.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8fbbe255-ee4d-440b-80b5-1da07966d708","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project doesn't exist yet, but the user says they built it. They're just asking how to configure `mcp.json`. I'll provide the configuration guidance.","outputTokens":335,"requestId":"158B:3932DE:333517E:37DF947:69FBE5D5"},"id":"9e04ab8e-1fdc-403e-acee-15e3c228c9cb","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:07:42.735Z","parentId":"adc7538a-4670-4865-9e48-9ed9e5c5f010"}
